php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Sundiata Jawanza","first_name":"Darvin","last_name":"Allen","aka":"Sundiata Jawanza","description":"Sundiata Jawanza, born Darvin Allen, has been imprisoned in the South Carolina state prison system since 1995, serving a life sentence for murder and accessory after the fact of armed robbery. He has expressed remorse for the offenses of his youth and during his three decades inside has become one of the most consequential prison-rights organizers in the United States.\n\nHe is a founder of Jailhouse Lawyers Speak, the prisoner-led network that since 2018 has organized national prison work strikes and the Free Alabama Movement-style campaigns against forced prison labor. He is Co-Chair of the National Lawyers Guild Mass Incarceration Committee and the Mass Defense Committee, and the Jailhouse Lawyer Vice President on the NLGs National Executive Committee. He is also an Imam who serves as the spiritual guide for the Muslim population in his facility, and a certified peer support specialist who teaches substance-use and mental-health classes inside.\n\nSouth Carolina prison authorities have responded to his organizing by holding him in closed custody. In April 2023 he was transferred to the Turbeville Correctional Institution to complete the Addiction Treatment Unit program in support of his parole eligibility. The Jericho Movement classifies him as a politicized prisoner — a person originally incarcerated for ordinary criminal charges who has become a political prisoner through subsequent organizing inside.","state":"South Carolina","race":"Black","gender":"Male","ideologies":["Prison abolition","Islam"],"affiliation":["Jailhouse Lawyers Speak","National Lawyers Guild Mass Incarceration Committee"],"inmate_number":"00233800","in_custody":true,"released":false,"cases":[{"institution_name":"Turbeville Correctional Institution","institution_city":"Turbeville","institution_state":"South Carolina","charges":"Murder; accessory after the fact of armed robbery","arrest_date":"1995-01-01","incarceration_date":"1995-01-01","sentence":"Life","convicted":"Yes — South Carolina state conviction, 1995"}]}'

php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Kwame Shakur","first_name":"Kwame","last_name":"Shakur","aka":"Kwame Beans Shakur","description":"Kwame Beans Shakur is the Chairman and Co-Founder of the New Afrikan Liberation Collective and National Director of the Prison Lives Matter Movement. He is held in the Indiana Department of Correction under inmate number 149677 and has been in solitary confinement for 23 to 24 hours a day for more than six years.\n\nHe was arrested in 2011 in Terre Haute, Indiana — his hometown and the city where his grandfather, Robert Joyner Sr., had been one of the leading 1960s and 1970s Black liberation organizers and a co-founder of what is now the Booker T. Washington Community Center. Indiana State Police, U.S. Marshals, and SWAT surrounded his fathers house with snipers and an armored vehicle. After a brief standoff he came out and was held for 33 days before being charged with the double homicide of two white men. He maintains his innocence; the only physical evidence seized in the warrantless search were the firearms that had belonged to his late grandfather. The prosecution introduced his street-organization (Growth and Development) affiliation extensively at trial. He was convicted and sentenced to 110 years.\n\nIn 2014, after being introduced by Comrade Shaka Shakur (also in this database) at the Pendleton Correctional Facility to the work of Sanyika Shakur and Jalil Muntaqim, he became a New Afrikan revolutionary nationalist. With Shaka Shakur he co-founded the New Afrikan Liberation Collective. The Jericho Movement classifies him as a politicized prisoner.","state":"Indiana","race":"Black","gender":"Male","ideologies":["New Afrikan Independence","Prison abolition"],"affiliation":["New Afrikan Liberation Collective","Prison Lives Matter"],"inmate_number":"149677","in_custody":true,"released":false,"cases":[{"institution_name":"Miami Correctional Facility","institution_city":"Bunker Hill","institution_state":"Indiana","charges":"Double homicide","arrest_date":"2011-01-01","incarceration_date":"2011-01-01","sentence":"110 years; held in solitary confinement 23–24 hours per day for political organizing inside","convicted":"Yes — Indiana state conviction"}]}'

php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Joseph Shine White Stewart","first_name":"Joseph","last_name":"Stewart","aka":"Shine White","description":"Joseph Shine White Stewart, North Carolina Department of Public Safety inmate number 0802041, has been incarcerated in the North Carolina state prison system for sixteen years. Originally entering prison as what he describes as a former street tribe member, he was politicized inside through the writings of George Jackson and the broader New Afrikan Independence Movement tradition; he became National Spokesperson of the New Afrikan Black Panther Party-Prison Chapter (NABPP-PC) and is a former leader of the White Panther Organization.\n\nHis political work inside has focused on raising the political consciousness of white prisoners in particular, attempting to counter the white-supremacist organizing that dominates U.S. prison yards and to confront the divide-and-conquer strategies that pit white, Black, and other prisoners of color against each other. In recent years he has lost much of his outside support network because of internal movement disputes — including his condemnation of another prisoner-organizer he believed to be an informant, a split inside the NABPP, and his identification with the writings of James Yaki Sayles, which some movement participants have considered taboo for a white organizer to claim. The Jericho Movement classifies him as a politicized prisoner.","state":"North Carolina","race":"White","gender":"Male","ideologies":["Prison abolition","New Afrikan Independence"],"affiliation":["New Afrikan Black Panther Party-Prison Chapter","White Panther Organization"],"inmate_number":"0802041","in_custody":true,"released":false,"cases":[{"institution_name":"Granville Correctional Institution","institution_city":"Phoenix","institution_state":"North Carolina","charges":"North Carolina state conviction (specifics pending verification); has served 16 years","arrest_date":"2008-01-01","incarceration_date":"2008-01-01","sentence":"North Carolina state prison sentence","convicted":"Yes — North Carolina state conviction"}]}'

